132nd MAINE LEGISLATURE
FIRST SPECIAL SESSION-2025
Legislative Document No. 1607
H.P. 1061 House of Representatives, April 15, 2025
An Act to Require Law Enforcement Agencies to Adopt Written
Policies Regarding Compliance with Certain Constitutional
Obligations Related to Disclosure of Evidence
(AFTER DEADLINE)
Approved for introduction by a majority of the Legislative Council pursuant to Joint Rule
205.
Received by the Clerk of the House on April 11, 2025. Referred to the Committee on
Criminal Justice and Public Safety pursuant to Joint Rule 308.2 and ordered printed pursuant to
Joint Rule 401.
ROBERT B. HUNT
Clerk
Presented by Representative BUNKER of Farmington.
Printed on recycled paper

1 Be it enacted by the People of the State of Maine as follows:
2 Sec. 1. 25 MRSA §2803-B, sub-§1, ¶N, as amended by PL 2023, c. 394, Pt. A,
3 §8, is further amended to read:
4 N. Unannounced execution of search warrants; and
5 Sec. 2. 25 MRSA §2803-B, sub-§1, ¶O, as enacted by PL 2023, c. 394, Pt. A, §9,
6 is amended to read:
7 O. By January 1, 2024, the confidentiality of attorney-client communications, which
8 must include, at a minimum, processes to protect and ensure confidentiality of
9 attorney‑client communications and processes to be followed in the event that there is
10 a breach of attorney‑client confidentiality.;
11 Sec. 3. 25 MRSA §2803-B, sub-§1, ¶P is enacted to read:
12 P. By January 1, 2026, requirements for the law enforcement agency to assist a
13 prosecuting agency in complying with the prosecuting agency's constitutional
14 obligations under Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and Giglio v. United States,
15 405 U.S. 150 (1972); and
16 Sec. 4. 25 MRSA §2803-B, sub-§1, ¶Q is enacted to read:
17 Q. By January 1, 2026, requirements for the law enforcement agency to comply with
18 mandatory disclosures to the Maine Criminal Justice Academy.
19 SUMMARY
2200 This bill requires that, by January 1, 2026, law enforcement agencies adopt written
2211 policies regarding procedures to deal with assisting a prosecuting agency in complying with
2222 the prosecuting agency's constitutional obligations under Brady v. Maryland (1963) and
2233 Giglio v. United States (1972) and regarding the requirement to comply with mandatory
2244 disclosures to the Maine Criminal Justice Academy.
